ing><DescriptorName UI="D016896" MajorTopicYN="N">Treatment Outcome</DescriptorName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D019008" MajorTopicYN="N">Drug Resistance, Neoplasm</DescriptorName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D008875" MajorTopicYN="N">Middle Aged</DescriptorName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D061067" MajorTopicYN="N">Antibodies, Monoclonal, Humanized</DescriptorName></MeshHeading></MeshHeadingList><OtherAbstract Type="plain-language-summary" Language="eng"><AbstractText>Penile squamous cell carcinoma (PSCC) is a rare but serious cancer with high mortality rates. Many patients do poorly if the disease comes back after taking chemotherapy. Few treatment options are available for these patients, and new treatment is urgently needed. Research in laboratory models of PSCC has suggested that combining two types of medicines together may help. One is a PARP inhibitor (Niraparib) that works by stopping cancer cells from repairing their DNA and the other (Dostarlimab) is an immune checkpoint therapy. This study will test the two drugs together. The goal is to see if this combination can shrink tumors, stop the cancer from growing, help patients live longer, and assess how safe it is for patients.</AbstractText></OtherAbstract><KeywordList Owner="NOTNLM"><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">Penile Neoplasms</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">Poly(ADP-ribose) polymerase inhibitors</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">combination</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">dostarlimab</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">drug therapy</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">immune checkpoint inhibitors</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">niraparib</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">phase II clinical trials</Keyword></KeywordList><CoiStatement>The authors have no relevant affiliations or financial involvement with any organization or entity with a financial interest in or financial conflict with the subject matter or materials discussed in the manuscript. 